x <- NULL
curve(dnorm(x, 10, 4), xlim = c(10 - 3*4, 10 + 3*4)) 
curve(dnorm(x, 10, 2), xlim = c(10 - 3*2, 10 + 3*2))   
curve(dnorm(x, 5, 10), xlim = c(5 - 3*10, 5 + 3*10))  
curve(dnorm(x, 10, 0.5), xlim = c(10 - 3*0.5, 10 + 3*0.5))

For the above plots, were plotting the normal functions with the above given characteristics related to mean and standard deviation. Note the spread and center are different based on these characteristics for each graph.

The below curves plot the normal function given the densities of each x value with the given mean and standard deviation. We then make a polygon thats colored red with x values from a certain width(depending on the probabilities), and then relate those x to the corresponding y. We start the y at 0 and end at 0 since at each point, the area of that slit is going to be 0. We can calculate the total area by simply using pnorm which doesnt reference our graph but essentially finds the probability that data falls into a certain part of the graph.

x <- NULL
curve(dnorm(x, 0, 1), xlim = c(0 - 3*1, 0 + 3*1))

# Define the range of the area to highlight 
xcurve <- seq(2, 10, length = 1000)  

# Calculate the density of the normal distribution for this range
ycurve <- dnorm(xcurve, 0, 1)

  
polygon(c(2, xcurve, 10), c(0, ycurve, 0), col = "red")

# Calculate the Area
area = pnorm(10, 0, 1) - pnorm(2, 0, 1) 
area
## [1] 0.02275013

The below curves plot the weibull function given the densities of each x value with the given shape(alpha) and scale(Beta). Weibull function is not related to the gamma function but is useful in modeling failure times, an example of this is failure of machinery. We then make a polygon thats colored red with x values from a certain width(depending on the probabilities), and then relate those x to the corresponding y. We start the y at 0 and end at 0 since at each point, the area of that slit is going to be 0. We can calculate the total area by simply using pweibull which doesnt reference our graph but essentially finds the probability that data falls into a certain part of the graph.

The below curves plot the beta function given the densities of each x value with the given shape1 and shape2. The beta function tends to be used for probabilities because it is within the range of 0 and 1. We then make a polygon thats colored red with x values from a certain width(depending on the probabilities) but must be betwee 0 and 1, and then relate those x to the corresponding y. We start the y at 0 and end at 0 since at each point, the area of that slit is going to be 0. We can calculate the total area by simply using pbeta which doesnt reference our graph but essentially finds the probability that data falls into a certain part of the graph.

x <- NULL
